Pass it on...
.
Try for a moment to comprehend how things you do and say effect other people's lives, as well as the knock on effect of your actions. How might things have changed if you'd have done something differently. Your actions may directly effect the outcome of someone's day, job interview, business meeting, first date - potentially influencing their life. .
Yes, I suppose I'm sort of toeing the line of an alternative and parallel existence; but really that's not really the point I'm trying to make. Think about how you can make a positive impact on those around you, and whilst you may not reap the rewards directly, be conscious that the good waves you made will be causing positive ripples through that person's life. .
More and more I realise that the smallest of niceties or compliments can have such a profound effect. So make sure each day you plant that seed of positivity; ask how their day's been, show thanks and appreciation, smile.

Moments...
.
Something so small that thousands pass by without you noticing; but upon reflection, a moment can be something that overpowers you with emotion, memories and meaning.
.
I was sat by a fire on a stone beach surrounded by high Scottish mountains, and relaxing walking for hours to reach camp for the night. The noise of the crackling wood was accompanied by the sounds of rolling waves crashing, and eagles screeching as they soared above. I was miles from civilisation, cut off from the world and everything that you'd call the modern world. In that instant nothing else but what was around me mattered. Everything beyond the light of the fire and the setting sun was out of control and out of reach. The only thing was that exact moment. Absolute zero - total tranquility and peace.
.

Sleeping giants...

We drove through dense fog and cloud, the kind that smothers and chokes the world, making the land appear flat and endless. The tall mountains of Glen Coe peeked at us through small gaps in the cloud, showing their dominance and presence and yet still remaining a mystery. I felt a sense that I was being watched intently and from all angles, like in the films where dozens of sets of eyes appear from the darkness - the sudden realisation that these huge ancient mountains encircled us on all sides, their true size and scale unknown, but constantly being aware of their presence. .

Who loves autumn? I really enjoy the colours and wild wild weather, not so much the darker evenings though. .

.

For around 3 weeks of the year the low winter sun rises directly through the famous arch of Durdle Door. .
To be in with a chance of catching it on one of these specific few weeks that the sun aligns perfectly you also need to have a perfectly clear sky, without any hint of clouds on the horizon. .
And then to top it off there's only a window of around 5 minutes when it actually shines through the arch, and is visible from the beach.
.
Where was I when this wonderous coincedence of the natural world was occuring, 300 yards down the beach running through the sand with my dog.

Win some, lose some, I guess.

As much as I don’t really like this shot, it’s an experience I wanted to share. Getting up close and personal with a glacier is something I’ve wanted to do for a long time, and ticking that off in Iceland was really bonus for me. .
I find them absolutely fascinating as a part of nature, from the way they’re formed, to carving out glaciers, or showing signs of climate change. .

If anyone wants to learn more on glaciers I’d really recommend watching Chasing Ice, great documentary that looks at climate change through the study of retreating ice. .
